{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.3","generated_at":"2026-04-29T17:45:29.511259+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 50 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 63 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":63,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":50,"completed_with_unit_data":50,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"v2.2":12,"v2.1":17,"v2.0":21},"missing_data_jsons":["2001","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2015","2016","2017","2018","2019","2021","2022"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2887,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 50 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -28.9%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":372,"p25":-0.4974,"median":-0.2887,"p75":-0.0634},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.0536,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 50 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +5.4%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":50,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":50,"min":-0.3361,"max":1.0927,"mean":0.1075,"median":0.0536,"p25":-0.1061,"p50":0.0536,"p75":0.2492,"p10":-0.2003,"p90":0.4551},"median_actual_dollars":221146.99},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~116 hours per plumbing unit","value":116.1347,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 116.1 hrs/unit (P25 99, P75 141). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 99 and 141 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":50,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":167.7512,"median":116.1347,"p25":98.7191,"p50":116.1347,"p75":141.4763,"p10":74.2942,"p90":165.6673,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 39.4%","value":0.3935,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 39.4%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":50,"p25":0.3268,"median":0.3935,"p75":0.4584},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$40.35/hr (1.43\u00d7 blended)","value":40.3504,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $40.35/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.43\u00d7 means OWP carries ~43% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":28.3488,"loaded_wage_median":40.3504,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4318},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-15.7% median)","value":-0.1565,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -15.7%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":472,"min":-0.9914,"max":3.4135,"mean":-0.0962,"median":-0.1565,"p25":-0.4163,"p50":-0.1565,"p75":0.0864,"p10":-0.5939,"p90":0.3996},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":50,"min":57.375,"max":2400.0,"mean":167.7512,"median":116.1347,"p25":98.7191,"p50":116.1347,"p75":141.4763,"p10":74.2942,"p90":165.6673,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":50,"min":1419.3979,"max":90082.0,"mean":5206.953,"median":3490.6273,"p25":2675.2377,"p50":3490.6273,"p75":4072.1856,"p10":1926.0269,"p90":4349.6272,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":50,"min":1219.6971,"max":58415.81,"mean":4548.499,"median":3361.2908,"p25":2802.1083,"p50":3361.2908,"p75":3989.787,"p10":2014.4458,"p90":4633.0801,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":50,"min":7181.5,"max":350295.0,"mean":21755.1077,"median":15493.5369,"p25":11612.616,"p50":15493.5369,"p75":17083.3744,"p10":9820.3781,"p90":19259.3205,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"labor_pct_of_revenue":{"n":50,"min":0.1089,"max":0.3355,"mean":0.2314,"median":0.2248,"p25":0.2077,"p50":0.2248,"p75":0.2624,"p10":0.1851,"p90":0.2798,"note":"Labor cost / revenue","unit":"fraction"},"material_pct_of_revenue":{"n":50,"min":0.0936,"max":0.3135,"mean":0.2292,"median":0.231,"p25":0.2083,"p50":0.231,"p75":0.